<a name=3D"cohc"></a>

<button class=3D"accordion">3. Effect size for mean differences of groups w=
ith unequal sample size within a pre-post-control design</button>
<div class=3D"panel">=09
	<br><br>
<p>Intervention studies usually compare the development of at least two gro=
ups (in general an experimental group and a control group). In many cases, =
the pretest means and standard deviations of both groups do not match and t=
here are a number of possibilities to deal with that problem. Klauer (2001)=
 proposes to compute g<sub><small></small></sub> for both groups and to sub=
tract them afterwards. This way, different sample sizes and pre-test values=
 are automatically corrected. The calculation is therefore equal to computi=
ng the effect sizes of both groups via <a href=3D"https://www.psychometrica=
.de/effect_size.html#cohenb">form 2</a> and afterwards to subtract both. Mo=
rris (2008) presents different effect sizes for repeated measures designs a=
nd does a simulation study. He argues to use the pooled pretest standard de=
viation for weighting the differences of the pre-post-means (so called d<su=
b><small>ppc2</small></sub> according to Carlson &amp; Smith, 1999). That w=
ay, the intervention does not influence the standard deviation. Additionall=
y, there are weighting to correct for the estimation of the population effe=
ct size. Usually, Klauer (2001) and Morris (2002) yield similar results.</p=
>
<p>The downside to this approach: The pre-post-tests are not treated as rep=
eated measures but as independent data. For dependent tests, you can use ca=
lculator <a href=3D"https://www.psychometrica.de/effect_size.html#repeated"=
>4</a> or <a href=3D"https://www.psychometrica.de/effect_size.html#dep">5</=
a> or <a href=3D"https://www.psychometrica.de/effect_size.html#tranfsorm">1=
3. transform eta square from repeated measures</a> in order to account for =
dependences between measurement points.</p>
