<i>eta;<small><sup>2</sup></small></i> at least interval scale and distribu=
tion assumptions are necessary. In case of categorical or ordinal data, oft=
en non-parametric approaches are used - in the case of statistical tests fo=
r example Wilcoxon or Mann-Whitney-U. The distributions of the their test s=
tatistics are approximated by normal distributions and finally, the result =
is used to assess significance. Accordingly, the test statistics can be tra=
nsformed in effect sizes (comp. Fritz, Morris &amp; Richler, 2012, p. 12; C=
ohen, 2008). Here you can find an effect size calculator for the test stati=
stics of the Wilcoxon signed-rank test, Mann-Whitney-U or Kruskal-Wallis-H =
in order to calculate <i>&#951;<small><sup>2</sup></small></i>. You alterna=
tively can directly use the resulting z value as well:</p>


