	<p><b>How to extract values from R (using lme4):</b></p>
	<pre style=3D"background-color:#f5f5f5; padding:10px; overflow-x:auto;">li=
brary(lme4)
fit &lt;- lmer(Y ~ X1 + X2 + (1|Z), data =3D mydata)

# For Method 1 (Coefficient &amp; SE):
summary(fit)              # Shows coefficients and SE
beta_X1 &lt;- fixef(fit)["X1"]
se_X1 &lt;- sqrt(diag(vcov(fit)))["X1"]
n &lt;- nrow(mydata)
p &lt;- length(fixef(fit))

# For Method 2 (t-statistic):
summary_fit &lt;- summary(fit)
t_value &lt;- summary_fit$coefficients["X1", "t value"]
var_beta &lt;- vcov(fit)["X1", "X1"]

# For Method 3 (R=B2):
# Use performance::r2() or MuMIn::r.squaredGLMM()
	</pre>
=09
	<p><b>Interpretation Guidelines:</b></p>
	<ul>
		<li><b>f=B2 =3D 0.02:</b> small effect</li>
		<li><b>f=B2 =3D 0.15:</b> medium effect</li>
		<li><b>f=B2 =3D 0.35:</b> large effect</li>
	</ul>
=09
	<p><small><b>Note on degrees of freedom:</b> In LMMs, df estimation can be=
 complex. The simple rule &#957; =3D n - p provides an approximation. For m=
ore precise estimation, consider Satterthwaite or Kenward-Roger approximati=
ons available in the lmerTest package.</small></p>
